The hygiene in the utilization of the toilet is also a preventive healthcare scheme. Global experts believe that the SBM will have saved over three lakh lives in the country by the time we become ‘open-defecation free’ in 2019.

As we have completed 4 years of the Swachhata scheme, 39% rural sanitation coverage has increased to a phenomenal 92%.This was not an easy goal to achieve. This involved a behavioural change of the people. This ‘people’s movement’ has today transformed into a ‘women’s movement’.

Swachhata campaign announced by the Prime Minister Shri Narendra Modi ji in his Independence Day speech of 2014, has been one scheme in the history of independent India which the people of India snatched away from the Government and converted into a ‘people’s movement.’

My vision for the future of mobility in India is based on 7 C’s: 1. Common. 2. Connected. 3. Convenient. 4. Congestion-free. 5. Charged. 6. Clean. 7. Cutting-edge: PM @narendramodipic.twitter.com/EPDkRJ2uS8

Clean Mobility powered by Clean Energy is our most powerful weapon in our fight against Climate Change. This means a pollution-free clean drive, leading to clean air and better living standards for our people. We should champion the idea of ‘clean kilometres’: PM

Charged mobility is the way forward. We want to drive investments across the value chain from batteries to smart charging to Electric Vehicle manufacturing. India’s entrepreneurs & manufacturers are now poised to develop and deploy break-through battery technology: PM

Indeed, India is on the MOVE. Our economy is on the MOVE. We are the world’s fastest-growing major economy. Our cities and towns are on the MOVE. We are building 100 smart cities. Our infrastructure is on the MOVE. We are speedily building roads, airports, rail lines & ports: PMpic.twitter.com/pk921fmVwU

Congestion free mobility is critical to check the economic and environmental costs of congestion. Hence, there should be emphasis on de-bottlenecking of networks. This would result in fewer traffic jams and lower levels of stress for commuters: PM

Convenient mobility means safe, affordable and accessible for all sections of the society. This includes the elderly, the women and the specially abled. We need to ensure that public transport is preferred to private modes of travel: PM

Connected mobility implies integration of geographies as well as modes of transport. The Internet-enabled Connected Sharing Economy is emerging as the fulcrum of mobility. We must leverage the full potential for vehicle pooling to improve private vehicle utilization: PM

Mobility is a key driver of the economy. Better mobility reduces the burden of travel and transportation and can boost economic growth. It is already a major employer and can create the next generation of jobs: PM Modi

Common Public Transport must be the cornerstone of our mobility initiatives. New business models driven by digitization, are reinventing the existing paradigm. Our focus must also go beyond cars, to other vehicles such as scooters and rickshaws: PM

సామాన్యుడికి మెరుగైన వైద్యాన్ని అందించాలన్నదే ప్రభుత్వ ధ్యేయం. ప్రాథమిక వైద్యకేంద్రాల్లో ఔట్ సోర్సింగ్ ద్వారా మెరుగైన వైద్య సదుపాయాలను కల్పిస్తున్నాము. అన్ని సబ్ సెంటర్లను, పంచాయతీ, అంగన్ వాడీ, స్కూళ్లు, శ్మశానాల నిర్మాణాలను గ్రామీణ ఉపాధి హామీ పథకంతో అనుసంధానిస్తున్నాము.

అసెంబ్లీ వర్షాకాల సమావేశాలు ప్రారంభం కానున్న నేపథ్యంలో వెంకటాయపాలెంలో ఎన్టీఆర్ విగ్రహానికి నివాళులర్పించాను. రాష్ట్రాభివృద్ధిలో మిగిలి ఉన్న లక్ష్యాలు, కేంద్రం నుంచి రాబట్టాల్సిన నిధులు వంటి కీలక అంశాలపై సమావేశాల్లో చర్చించనున్నాం.pic.twitter.com/Wq71nCGjMe

डॉ. रमन सिंह जी छत्तीसगढ़ में 50 लाख लोगों को स्मार्टफोन दे रहे हैं। कुछ दिन पहले कांग्रेस के राष्ट्रीय अध्यक्ष छत्तीसगढ़ आये थे और कह रहे थे कि रमन सिंह सरकार ‘BHEL' का फोन क्यों नहीं देती। देश का बच्चा-बच्चा जनता है पर अब उन्हें कौन समझाए की ‘BHEL' फोन ही नही बनाती।pic.twitter.com/g94BKsSgFy

IPPB will offer a range of products such as savings and current accounts, money transfer, direct benefit transfers, bill and utility payments, and enterprise and merchant payments.

On the day of launch, IPPB will have 650 Branches and 3250 Access Points spread across the country. Simultaneous launch events will be held at these branches and access points. All the 1.55 lakh Post Offices in the country will be linked to the IPPB system by December 31, 2018.

It will leverage the vast network of the Department of Posts, which covers every corner of the country with more than 300,000 Postmen and Grameen Dak Sewaks. IPPB will hence significantly augment the reach of the banking sector in India.

Later today, PM @narendramodi will launch India Post Payments Bank (IPPB) at a programme in Delhi. IPPB has been envisioned as an accessible, affordable and trusted bank for the common citizen, to help speedily achieve the financial inclusion objectives of the Union Government.
